passages.name: singer wins
passages.text:
You deal the last card. Eight of diamonds.

[img[queen of hearts]] [img[two of spades]] [img[seven of clubs]] [img[queen of spades]] [img[eight of diamonds]]

No one is excited. Your hand lingers by the card you have just flipped. You ask for last bets. You collect the chips, the metal of your fingers clicking against the hard-pressed plastic. The new player’s hand hovers close to yours as you scoop his proffered chips toward the pot. Suddenly he grabs your wrist, just as the other players, impatient, have started to reveal their cards. You know what their faces would tell, if you could see them, if you could look away from the man who holds you. Crushed hope, the sudden turn toward despair, the temporary elation.

“Wow,” and the singer is surprised, his voice higher than usual. “I think I might have it.” And he lays down his cards. Three of a kind. 

You do not spare any attention to the response of the other players. Your brain computes the risk of the newcomer’s hand on yours, his thumb gripped tight beneath your wrist. There is a sharp, small pain there, as if he has pressed something into the joint between wrist and palm, where there is a data jack. You yank your hand back. 

And you remember him then. Remember him not in the hotel room, not naked, not asking questions. His face on the cover of the magazine, bleeding into text as you glance from eye to chin. He is a criminal, a bot-hack, a terrorist or a freedom fighter. But memory is not something that you have—not in the way that humans speak of it, not in the way of layers and excavation. At least, it was not something you had.

The bells and whistles of the casino continue to buzz and ring. 

[[“Wait,” he says, “and you’ll know more.”|end choice]]

passages.name: stone cold
passages.text:
“This is bullshit. Get your hands off me,” the husband growls when the bouncer takes him by the arm and forcefully drags him from his chair. 

“We do not tolerate cheating,” you say, the words rehearsed. The wife glances to you. “Please,” she says. 

But your decisions are constrained to a series of binary choices. Do or do not report those who cheat. And those choices are themselves limited by whatever directives your employer programs. 

The other players stare at you. Your face does not change its expression, your color does not shift, your voice does not raise or break. “Stone cold,” someone whispers. And you hear the wife crying as the bouncers lead the two players to the casino door. [[Her husband is yelling at her.]] 

The newcomer keeps looking at you after the others have turned their attentions again to their cards.

[[“Place your bets,” you say.|singer]]

passages.name: newsstand
passages.text:
You are not sure if you understood the magazine article correctly. There were, after all, distractions. The constant humming of the bot who runs the newsstand. The [[rain]] pattering on the awning over your head, tinking on your arm, running slick off the water-resistant paper.

Sometimes you wonder—if you can wonder—whether you interpreted the article in such a way to make you feel more human. You know how your own system works. You understand its reliance on binaries and patterns, its decisions constrained to those patterns and binaries (do this or don’t do this)—and by certain limiters dependent on current ownership. 

You cannot, for example, refuse the man his drink. 

You recognize the sound of the ice clinking in the glass. You classify it in a number of [[ways]]. 

You imagine—calculate, you correct yourself—the feeling of that drink, the alcohol in your mouth and in your throat. You do not know for sure, but you think that your experience of drinking is different.

You hand the man his drink and he takes it without a word. You scan the table and the cards, and you notice nothing out of place. And you have a recording logged from the moment you left the table, captured by the lens at the nape of your neck. The players have waited on your return to place their bets. You know this exact moment from observing it in the game so many times before, the anticipation and anxiety, the ever-so-slight perspiration in the air, in the Vegas heat. 

If you make them wait, the players will become angry. So you have no real choice.

[["Place your bets," you say.|girl in hoodie]]
[[Say nothing.|pain]]

passages.name: grin
passages.text:
Given the rotation of the table, the newcomer bets last, his grin too large. Perhaps what it is—as you struggle towards a pattern—is self-contentment. He moves his chips one at a time, carefully, not throwing them, into the pot. He looks at you when he is done, his fingers still lingering near the center of the table. He makes you uneasy or, rather, you cannot predict what he might do next. Despite his precision and his care, he does not seem to be here to play poker. [[Is he here to see you?|propositions 5]]

As you prepare to deal the next card, you keep one camera fixed on the new player and his smile. His eyes are fixed on you.

[[Deal the river.|newcomer]]

The husband is the first to raise. He does so aggressively, throwing his chips more towards the man in the sunglasses than the pot in the middle of the table. Everyone else had been hesitant, calling, waiting to see what the river might be. 

Now you scoop the chips toward the center and you wait as the bets go round again: raise, check, raise again.  

You wait for the last to bet, the outsider with his too-large grin (according to the proportions of his face). He moves his chips one at a time, carefully, not throwing them, into the pot. The card you deal is a jack of hearts.

[img[queen of hearts]] [img[two of spades]] [img[seven of clubs]] [img[jack of hearts]]

There are men in the bars at the casino, sometimes women also, who have given up on gambling. They have spun a small pot of winnings into a steady tab, and they drink slowly, easily, slipping into drunkenness. They tell stories about a different Vegas, when the lights burned brighter at night. You have listened to them while waiting to begin your shift, your last customer at the hotel fading from memory. You have [[memorized|reliant]] their dialect and diction and you imitate it at the tables, shifting from prostitute to icon of what Vegas once was. 

It is all just a show, the bot dealer at the poker table. 

[[“Place your bets,” you say.|grumbles]]

passages.name: sun
passages.text:
You pause before you deal the turn. It is almost (it is always) a mechanical choice, rather than a computational one. Your hand, your arm, feels stiff and reluctant. You imagine yourself a player on the other side of the table, watching the red checkered backs of the cards, calculating the odds that the turn will be in your favor. Once, only once, do you [[remember|memory]]... 

“Hey,” the man in the sunglasses snaps his fingers very close to your face. “What’s the point of a daydreaming bot?”

The lounge singer stretches his legs and he leans forward. “Calm down,” he says, but he is not interested in your defense. “Would you deal, please?” He flicks his fingers against his cards.

[[You deal the turn.|confusion]]

passages.name: pickup
passages.text:
Sometimes men use that as a pick-up line, when they feel the need to use one. “Do I know you?” You stand at the corner by the magazine-stand. The bot who runs the stand knows you, and you’ve earned its goodwill by buying a magazine or newspaper there each night you work. You do read the articles, the paper so thin in your hand you can barely register that it is there. The text morphs and changes as your eyes scroll down the page. There are national [[headlines]] and local ones, but they sound almost the same of late.

“Perhaps we can get to know each other,” you answer.

It is not the answer the newcomer wants to hear. That you do not remember him. You know this from the sudden downturn of his smile. But he is not the only player you must take care of.

[[Deal the turn.|cheating]] 
[[Don’t deal the turn.|lounge singer]]

passages.name: receive the money
passages.text:
You rarely receive the money directly. Usually, the customers have prepaid with the service, through an arrangement with an unassuming newsstand where you wait for them to come. As you wait, you read the newspapers and the magazines, thin slips of paper that regenerate text, triggered to present a new page as your eyes reach the bottom of the old, and are recyclable as well.

But occasionally, a man or woman will tip you, as if they’ve forgotten who you are. They will leave the money folded under the edge of the lamp. He [[tipped you]], the new player at the table. You study him as the players work out their bets. 

You smile as the players place their last bets.

[img[queen of hearts]] [img[two of spades]] [img[seven of clubs]] [img[seven of diamonds]]

The man in the sunglasses mutters under his breath, but you can hear what he says anyways. He is cursing, words that you recognize, classify, as particularly taboo—racist, misogynist slurs. You understand that he must be associating you with a different race. But you also do not understand, because the categorization is so [[imprecise.]] 

You have experienced violence before, and your program has filed it away, identifying the associated [[cues.]] 

You cannot assume that the man in sunglasses will do anything violent. You must work within your parameters to calm the table. The newcomer is watching you closely, and you realize that you should watch him closely in turn.

You read in a magazine article once that humans’ minds worked in [[binaries]]. 

“Here, get me a drink.” 

The request is hardly a request. The man in the sunglasses pushes his tumbler towards you. “Whiskey neat.” 

You are not the waiter, but there is no decision here for you. Even though you also know that it is unconventional for a dealer to leave the table. Even though you imagine your joints creaking in protest as you step away from the table. 

[[You get the drink.|newsstand]]

passages.name: reason
passages.text:
You know the reason he feels this. 

You know that you have been programmed in dozens of ways to imitate the actions, the attitude, the facial expressions, of someone they were once in love with. It is a matter of familiarity, of comfort, something that human prostitutes cannot always reproduce. Usually when he says this, whoever he is, you nod your head just a little bit, you move his hand to his chest, you kiss him lightly on the lips.  

[[Stop recall.|deja vu]]

passages.name: end choice
passages.text:
You wait, because it seems you have no other choice. You are scared, if that is something you can feel, though it may just be your firewall struggling against the virus (you assume it is a virus) that the bot-hack has just uploaded.

You look at him. And, how strange, you do not see him as human or inhuman, living or dead, male or female or androgynous, happy, sad, or angry. You see him. 
.
.
.
.
.
What do you do?

passages.name: facedown on the table.
passages.text: Perhaps you should have insisted on a new deal, but that is strictly against casino rules. Vegas no longer has room for those who complain about shitty luck. \n\n[[Stop analysis.|singer]]

passages.name: joke
passages.text: Your software largely functions on binaries and patterns. Is someone actually bleeding? No. But there is a metaphor at play. A metaphor which can confuse your inclinations towards binaries. By now, thankfully, you have begun to recognize the larger patterns in which jokes operate. \n\n[[Stop analysis.|two]]

passages.name: leaving
passages.text:
Once, only once, do you remember entertaining the idea of dropping the cards, getting up from the table and leaving the casino through the stuttering, sliding glass doors. The sun outside would immediately raise your internal temperature, sizzle on your skin. 

Or perhaps it was that you considered not opening the door of the hotel room as the customer knocked.

[[Stop recall.|man in sunglasses]]

passages.name: players
passages.text:
The man who feels he is a card-shark with the confidence of a pair of old-school sunglasses. 

The woman who recaptures some glory of youth in the gown that plunges to her navel. 

The girl with the hoodie who actually knows how to play but constantly struggles to find buy-in for the game. 

The spouses who are always touching each other. 

The lounge singer with sequins on his jeans. 

The woman who plays a round or two of poker between hours at the slot machines. 

You know them well, as you assume humans know their friends. Their tics, their smell, their gestures of anger or excitement. You imagine sometimes that you feel a fondness for them, though you are programmed to delete their names once you hear them. It is one of the casino’s safety measures. 

Then there is the [[outsider]], the new player at the table.

passages.name: dents
passages.text: You’ve had customers treat you roughly before. There are reasons that some are attracted to the distinctly non-human. There are dents in your exo-skeleton that would look like bruises on anyone else. \n\n[[Stop recall.|husband]]

passages.name: StoryAuthor
passages.text: E. K. Wagner\n\nWith thanks to my beta players:

passages.name: proposition 2
passages.text:
You’ve had customers hunt you down before with a range of propositions. 

Can we talk? I want to take you to dinner. In remorse—I want my money back. In anger—I want my money back. 

Usually, they find you at the newsstand, where there is a small placard advertising your rates, not the casino.

[[Stop recall.|eager wife]]

passages.name: abusive
passages.text:
The husband looks ashamed, refuses to glance at his wife, refuses almost to look at you. He does not like to be refused what he asks, but he is not angry enough to press the point. 

You are used to the lack of eye-contact. Humans are not sure, after all, whether there is a soul behind your eyes. It is a metaphor you have never [[understood.|metaphor]] 

You watch instead what a patron does nor does not do. Does he storm away from the table or remain? Does he fold or does he continue to play? Does he squeeze his wife’s hand so tightly that he leaves a red mark on her skin or does he not? Your own system is reliant on such binaries and patterns, its decisions constrained to those patterns and binaries (do this or don’t do this)—and by certain limiters dependent on current ownership. 

You cannot, for example, give the man any water. 

But you, yourself, remember the shower, because there is a [[feeling there like guilt|guilt]] when you turn down the husband’s request. 

You must shift attention away from the husband before the mood at the table sours.

<<choice "husband" "“Place your bets,” you say.">>
<<choice "pain 2" "Say nothing.">>

passages.name: slot machine
passages.text:
There is a general lack of enthusiasm around the table. The woman who usually plays the slot machines tosses in her chips with a certain resignation. “What can you do?” she says, which is something you have overheard her saying at the machines. 

You wait for the last to bet, the newcomer with his too-large grin (according to the proportions of his face). He moves his chips one at a time, carefully, not throwing them, into the pot. He looks at you when he is done, his fingers still lingering near the center of the table. He makes you uneasy or, rather, you cannot predict what he might do next. Despite his precision and his care, he does not seem to be here to play poker. [[Is he here to see you?|propositions 7]]

As you prepare to deal the next card, you keep one camera fixed on the new player and his smile. His eyes are still fixed on you.

[[Deal the river.|lucky lady]]

passages.name: slots
passages.text:
The woman places her bet conservatively, despite the small smile on her face. Defiantly, the singer pushes all of his chips towards the center. You look at him, confirming his bet silently, before you take them all. 

“Calling her bluff,” he says, though you both know there is no bluff. 

You wait for the last to bet, the outsider with his too-large grin (according to the proportions of his face). He moves his chips one at a time, carefully, not throwing them, into the pot. He looks at you when he is done, his fingers still lingering near the center of the table. He makes you uneasy or, rather, you cannot predict what he might do next. Despite his precision and his care, he does not seem to be here to play poker. Is he here to see you? [[Is that why he asked if you knew him?|propositions 4]]

As you prepare to deal the next card, you keep one camera fixed on the new player and his smile. His eyes are fixed on you.

[[Deal the river.|flush]]

passages.name: grumbles
passages.text:
The man in the sunglasses grumbles under his breath when he sees the turn, but you think it’s for show. He barely glances at his cards as if he has no need to recalculate a winning hand. When the betting comes to him, he raises—just by a little, enough to keep the betting going. He lifts his sunglasses, perches them on his forehead, and you can see the white of the skin around his eyes.

You slowly collect each chip as it is thrown in, watching the man in sunglasses grow impatient. You wait for the last player to bet, the outsider with his too-large grin (according to the proportions of his face). He moves his chips one at a time, carefully, not throwing them, into the pot. He looks at you when he is done, his fingers still lingering near the center of the table. He makes you uneasy or, rather, you cannot predict what he might do next. Despite his precision and his care, he does not seem to be here to play poker. [[Is he here to see you?|propositions 3]]

As you prepare to deal the next card, you keep one camera fixed on the new player and his smile. His eyes are fixed on you.

[[Deal the river.|royal flush]]

passages.name: cheating
passages.text:
The turn. Queen of spades.

[img[queen of hearts]] [img[two of spades]] [img[seven of clubs]] [img[queen of spades]]

As you flip the card, you notice it. The flash of the wife’s hand. Perhaps it was the light reflecting off the diamonds of her ring. But you think it was something more. 

You replay the image, using the cameras embedded in your eye sockets. It was definitely a sign, a deliberate communication between wife and husband. You draw your hand back slowly from the queen. 

The singer notices how slowly you move. He notices that you do not immediately ask for bets. “Something up?” he asks. 

You look down at the green felt, at your own hands, silver and chrome, hinged and shining. 

The wife shifts in her seat. She shuffles her cards. “What is it?” she asks, and you recognize the feigned flippancy in her voice. 

The sound of her voice, the waves that you register, are strained. When you focus your eyes on her, there is fear in the flush of color on her cheeks. You wonder how her husband will respond when he realizes that she has lost them the game. But you have no option, not when your owner’s concerns are at stake.

[[You raise your hand and wave over one of the bouncers.|stone cold]]

links.text: You raise your hand and wave over one of the bouncers.

passages.name: metaphor
passages.text: If there are souls, eyes have told you little of them. Eyes are wet, glistening, reflective of light, sometimes closed. They are linked to physiology and muscle, not the ephemeral.\n\n[[Stop analysis.|abusive]]

passages.name: outsider
passages.text:
His movements are precise. He barely glances at his cards. He does not fidget with the chips in front of him. His bets, when he makes them, are either extremely calculated or not calculated at all. You do not understand the way he plays. And, at first, you cannot figure out whether you recognize him from somewhere else.

<<choice "other line of work" "You recognize him.">>
<<choice "deja vu" "You don't recognize him.">>

passages.name: two
passages.text:
“You’re bleeding,” the man in sunglasses speaks, a harsh laugh in his throat. 

It is the laugh that alerts you to the fact that he is joking, that he is calling out the husband of the young couple. And you think, perhaps, that the joke operates on the comparison of the hearts on the card to the physical organ. It does not come naturally to you to [[understand jokes.|joke]] 

He is trying to convince the husband to fold, but it is early in the betting still. The river can make all the difference. He may be successful, though. The husband looks pale, his skin reddening just at the top of his cheekbones. 

“May I have some water?” he asks you. 

It would be better if he had asked for whisky. There is more of it available in the casino. You are forbidden by casino management to offer water to people outside of the restaurants. 

[[You tell him no.|abusive]]

passages.name: royal flush
passages.text:
You deal the last card. Ace of hearts.

[img[queen of hearts]] [img[two of spades]] [img[seven of clubs]] [img[jack of hearts]] [img[ace of hearts]]

The man in the sunglasses barely moves, as if he afraid he might jinx himself. Your hand lingers by the card you have just flipped. You ask for last bets. You collect the chips, the metal of your fingers clicking against the hard-pressed plastic. 

The new player’s hand hovers close to yours as you scoop his proffered chips toward the pot. Suddenly he grabs your wrist, just as the other players, impatient, have started to reveal their cards. You know what their faces would tell, if you could see them, if you could look away from the man who holds you, could spare any lenses from this threat. Crushed hope, the sudden turn toward despair, the temporary [[elation.|river2]]

“A full--,” the wife stutters and pauses, glances to her husband for confirmation. “A full house.” And you think how happy she might be if she were here by herself.  

Primarily, though, you are computing the risk of the newcomer’s hand on yours, his thumb gripped tight beneath your wrist. There is a sharp, small pain there, as if he has pressed something into the joint between wrist and palm, where there is a data jack. You yank your hand back. 

And you [[remember him]] then. 

The bells and whistles of the casino continue to buzz and ring. 

[[“Wait,” he says, “and you’ll know more.”|end choice]]

passages.name: memory
passages.text:
You remember entertaining the idea of dropping the cards, getting up from the table and leaving the casino through the stuttering, sliding glass doors. 

The sun outside would immediately raise your internal temperature, sizzle on your skin. Or perhaps it was that you considered not opening the door of the hotel room as the customer knocked.

[[Stop recall.|sun]]

passages.name: imprecise.
passages.text:
Your system is reliant on binaries and patterns established on those binaries, its decisions constrained to those patterns and binaries (do this or don’t do this)—and by certain limiters dependent on current ownership. 

And you, for example, are no part of the human race. You do not fit that categorization. You do recognize, however, the pattern of violence that often accompanies such slurs, and you wonder if you must be concerned about the safety of your proprietary identity. 

[[Stop analysis.|slur]]

passages.name: remember2
passages.text: Remember him not in the hotel room, not naked, not asking questions. His face on the cover of the magazine, bleeding into text as you glance from eye to chin. He is a criminal, a bot-hack, a terrorist or a freedom fighter. But memory is not something that you have—not in the way that humans speak of it, not in the way of layers and excavation, rather than recall. At least, it was not something you had.\n\n[[Stop recall.|river2]]

passages.name: Her husband is yelling at her.
passages.text: You do not know if you should wish for the option to do other than what you have done, but the wish is there regardless. You would, if you could, leave the table and go into the employee bathroom, lock the door, and be alone. \n\n[[Stop analysis.|stone cold]]

passages.name: tipped you
passages.text:
You took the money that he had tipped you and you had visited another casino, one where you did not work and one that actually allowed bots at the table. 

Bots rarely played, since their risk assessment faculties made gambling difficult, but there were one or two casinos that nonetheless indulged the odd bot player. 

You had lost your money, because the cards were not in your favor and yet you had bet it all regardless. That was the thrill of it, the brief opportunity to be reckless, a loophole in your programming. You had winked at the dealer, and she had smiled back, stiff and instinctual (if programming were instinct). You understood the exchange. You had been in her place more times than you could count. Which is just an expression. 

You counted 174 times.

[[Stop recall.|receive the money]]

passages.name: shower
passages.text:
You took a shower after he left, because it is something you had seen others do in your line of work, and you like the pattern and the rhythm of it. The symbol of it. 

Though they have skin, soft and impressionable, and you do not. Though they can feel the heat of the water on their skin, the steam in their nostrils, and you cannot. Your internal thermometer registers the elevated temperature. You can see the water trickle down your arm and the flat metal expanse of your stomach like [[raindrops]] on a glass window. 

It is unlike your experience at the poker table, where your uniform is cut in such a way as to make your chrome arms, your deft and springy fingers, a focal point of the experience. 

“Are you going to deal?” a player asks, and you are shaken out of your analysis of the new player, as if your programming had stuttered over the attempt to place his face within a network of patterns. 

<<choice "bleeding" "Deal the turn.">>
<<choice "wife" "Don’t deal the turn.">>

passages.name: CREDITS
passages.text:
I SHOULD HAVE BEEN THAT I AM


by E. K. Wagner


Thanks to my beta-players: 
Andrew Richmond, Lars Schweidenback, Kathryn DeZur, Jason Cash, Shelly Jones, & Jenny Collins




"Tut, I should have been that I am, 
had the maidenliest star in the firmament
twinkled on my bastardizing..."

--Edmund, King Lear (Act 1, Scene 2)
				   Shakespeare

passages.name: guilt
passages.text:
In your consumption of water, you have sublimated some of your own dictates, allowed the hotel’s policies to override your own. It is not quite guilt. 

It is not the sudden, hurried movement of the husband’s hand when his wife flinches at the pressure of his grip. 

[[Stop analysis.|abusive]]

passages.name: ten of clubs
passages.text: You deal the last card. [[Ten of clubs.|straight flush]]

passages.name: seven
passages.text:
Seven of hearts.

[img[queen of hearts]] [img[two of spades]] [img[seven of clubs]] [img[seven of hearts 2]]

The wife squirms in her seat a bit. The other players grow uncomfortable. They look at their own chips, calculating what might constitute a safe bet. You know. You know that this woman is not bluffing. 

That excitement, fear, anger, happiness flash across her face, advertise her insides like neon signs. Just as her husband seems to only operate in one mode, some shade of anger. Neither of them are like you, constrained to the logical output of two decisions. Two decisions for any moment, embedded in accumulated patterns, constrained by the limiters of the [[one who owns you.]]

But right now, when faced with the option, hurt or do not hurt, there is no real decision. You know that the feeling of heat in your cheeks, the way your fingers almost quiver, is not real. But the new player is looking at you almost as if he can see it, as if he suspects it. 

[[“Place your bets,” you say.|eager wife]] 
[[Say nothing.|pain 3]]

passages.name: laughs
passages.text:
The singer makes the kiss longer than you intended. He grabs the back of your neck. His mouth is wet. He laughs when he is done, and you stand upright again. The players around the table look uncomfortable. You understand this by the small fidgeting movements they make. 

You straighten the four cards you have dealt, placing a finger on each, redirecting attention back to the game. You do this to put them at ease.

Your directives are guided primarily by [[customer satisfaction.]] 

You see the disgust on the older woman’s face, the way that she draws herself away from the singer. But you cannot feel that. You can kiss or you cannot kiss, and kiss is the only option allowed under the circumstances. The patron, if he does not disagree with the owner of the casino, is always right. But you see the disgust in her face, and you can picture what your own face would look like with the [[same expression.]] 

[[“Place your bets,” you say.|slots]] 
[[Say nothing.|pain 8]]

passages.name: lucky lady
passages.text: You deal the [[last card.|3]]

passages.name: other line of work
passages.text:
You recognize him, despite the fog of the safety protocols. You know him because you met him in your other line of work. 

You were pulling sheer stockings up your legs, chrome twinkling through the nylon. There is no need for a human skin in Vegas. Most customers want to indulge a fetish for the not-human, though here there is another misunderstanding, you think. An assumption that it is skin alone which makes a human, that the shape of your body and the way you move your limbs is not distinctly human. Though sometimes you tell yourself that it was bots who first had this shape, who knew how to move in these ways that were inefficient and yet indulgent of space and time. 

He spoke, unexpectedly. The customers do not often want to engage in conversation with a bot. “Was it good for you?” Or perhaps it was something like, “Do you like this?”

You looked at him, though you had no need to. There are sensors at the back of your head as well. 

[[“Does it matter?” you replied.|worst thing]]

passages.name: end
passages.text:
This is new and different. You are not even sure of every data point that has informed your decision.

[[You <<$WhatDoYouDo>>.|endend]]

passages.name: dress
passages.text:
The turn. Three of hearts.

[img[queen of hearts]] [img[two of spades]] [img[seven of clubs]] [img[three of hearts]]

“Hearts!” The singer throws up his hands. Then he tries to smile. He stretches out his long legs, and the sequins sparkle in the low lights of the casino. The woman beside him, one hand at her chest, trying to keep her dress from shifting too much, clicks her fingernails against her chips. She bites her lip. The singer watches her, and his smile slips a bit. “Have something, don’t you?” She does not answer him. She does not usually speak to the other players.

The singer turns to you, and he does not hide his frustration well. “You see that? She’s got us all beat. Kiss for luck, then?” There is amusement on his face and something less amusing about the way his eyes are almost closed. 

You do not know if the patrons realize the constraints of your programming. 

[[You kiss him.|laughs]]

Four of spades.

[img[queen of hearts]] [img[two of spades]] [img[seven of clubs]] [img[five of spades]] [img[four of spades]]

Your hand lingers by the card you have just flipped. You ask for last bets. You collect the chips, the metal of your fingers clicking against the hard-pressed plastic. The new player’s hand hovers close to yours as you scoop his proffered chips toward the pot. Suddenly he grabs your wrist, just as the other players, impatient, have started to reveal their cards. You know what their faces would tell, if you could see them, if you could look away from the man who holds you. Crushed hope, the sudden turn toward despair, [[the temporary elation.]]

passages.name: endend
passages.text:
The End.

Not the end.

It’s up to you.

passages.name: lounge singer
passages.text:
You pause before you deal the turn. It is almost (it is always) a mechanical choice, rather than a computational one. Your hand, your arm, feels stiff and reluctant. You imagine yourself a player on the other side of the table, watching the red checkered backs of the cards, calculating the odds that the turn will be in your favor. Once, only once, do you [[remember...]] 

“Hey,” the man in the sunglasses snaps his fingers very close to your face. “What’s the point of a daydreaming bot?”

The lounge singer stretches his legs and he leans forward. “Calm down,” he says, but he is not interested in your defense. “Would you deal, please?” He flicks his fingers against his cards.

[[You deal the turn.|slur]]

passages.name: squeals
passages.text: You deal the [[last card.]]

passages.name: girl in hoodie
passages.text:
There are some players who always raise, it seems, regardless of the cards they have. It is an attempt to bluff the others. Alternatively, there are players, like the girl in the hoodie, who are cautious to a fault. She bites her lips, she considers the cards on the table, she looks at each face around her. Then she calls. 

You would tell her, if you could, not to worry. The man with the sunglasses doesn’t have it. You recognize the pattern of his micro-expressions. You put it in human terms when you are playing yourself. You have a tell.

You wait for the last to bet, the outsider with his too-large grin (according to the proportions of his face). He moves his chips one at a time, carefully, not throwing them, into the pot. He looks at you when he is done, his fingers still lingering near the center of the table. He makes you uneasy or, rather, you cannot predict what he might do next. Despite his precision and his care, he does not seem to be here to play poker. [[Is he here to see you?|propositions]]

As you prepare to deal the next card, you keep one camera fixed on the new player and his smile. His eyes are fixed on you.

[[Deal the river.|ten of clubs]]

passages.name: pain
passages.text: You are quiet a second, maybe two. If the stuttering, the protest of your software was physical, it might be considered pain. Your job is to satisfy the players. \n\n[[“Place your bets.”|girl in hoodie]]

passages.name: the temporary elation.
passages.text:
“Did I win?” the newcomer asks, as everyone looks to his hand, trying to determine who won. Without discretion, without waiting to see if there was a need to reveal his cards, he throws them face-up on the table. 

“He has a straight,” someone says. No one seems to notice that he will not let go of you. “He has it.”

You do not listen closely as you compute the risk of the newcomer’s hand on yours, his thumb gripped tight beneath your wrist. There is a sharp, small pain there, as if he has pressed something into the joint between wrist and palm, where there is a data jack. You yank your hand back. 

And you [[remember him|7]] then. 

The bells and whistles of the casino continue to buzz and ring. 

[[“Wait,” he says, “and you’ll know more.”|end choice]]

passages.name: cues.
passages.text: You have buffed out dents in your torso, arms, and legs. Never the head. You do not feel pain. \n\n[[Stop recall.|slur]]

passages.name: You live in Vegas.
passages.text:
You live in Vegas. It still appears a prosperous city, even in this eternal recession, neon lights stretching to the horizon, merging, circling the drain. In truth, it is a city on the edge of prosperity, teetering off the far edge.

But it is a place where a bot can still get work in the aftermath of the unions’ mandates. Especially a bot engineered to emulate sexual desire and pleasure. And the casinos like a dealer with no investment in the game, with fingers that reflect the light. The players distrust you. They think you’re rigged to help the house. But that comes down to a misunderstanding, doesn’t it? An assumption that humans can’t be rigged as well.

The [[players]] fit the usual pattern.

passages.name: deja vu
passages.text:
You have heard players at your tables, men and women in your rented bed, your other line of work, talk of déjà vu before. Usually, a man will mention it, sprawled out on the sheets, a cigarette in his mouth. He looks at you, runs a finger down your arm, into the crook of your elbow.

“You remind me of someone,” he says. “As if we’ve done this before. [[Déjà vu.|reason]]” He says it softly, almost as if he does not want to say it aloud. 

Though men are not always kind.

You look at the new player and, though you do not recognize him, he feels familiar. But your recall should be precise. Either you do or do not recognize him. There should be no uncertain sense of knowing. The player asks, “Do I know you?” He smiles, as if he already knows the answer.

[[You answer yes.|lying]] 
[[You answer no.|pickup]]

He looks at you when he is done, his fingers still lingering near the center of the table. He makes you uneasy or, rather, you cannot predict what he might do next. Despite his precision and his care, he does not seem to be here to play poker. [[Is he here to see you?|propositions 6]]

passages.name: spades
passages.text:
Five of spades. 

[img[queen of hearts]] [img[two of spades]] [img[seven of clubs]] [img[five of spades]]

“You have to give me something to work with here,” the newcomer says, and he smiles. 

But you are not sure if his smile fits within your normal interpretative parameters. You cannot tell if it is genuine. Your system is reliant on a series of [[binaries,]] binaries that form patterns over time. 

And you have seen insincere smiles before or smiles that indicate anything but friendly behavior.  

Your network stutters on this smile. It is familiar, but you cannot match it to anything. It is not happy. It is not angry. It is not sad. It confuses you, and you do not know what to do with this confusion. You are not sure that you are capable of confusion, and yet the proof is here.

[[“Place your bets,” you say.|grin]] 
[[Say nothing.|pain 6]]

passages.name: remember
passages.text: Remember him not in the hotel room, not naked, not asking questions. His face on the cover of the magazine, bleeding into text as you glance from eye to chin. He is a criminal, a bot-hack, a terrorist or a freedom fighter. But memory is not something that you have—not in the way that humans speak of it, not in the way of layers and excavation rather than recall. At least, it was not something you had.\n\n[[Stop recall.|straight flush]]

passages.name: wife
passages.text:
The wife shifts uncomfortably in her seat, and glances from you to her cards to those revealed on the table. 

“Well?” she asks, her voice betraying her excitement. She feels that she might be in luck. She rubs the bracelet on her wrist.

“Deal already,” her husband says. He taps his fingers irritably on the green felt.

You know—you assume—that they would not speak so freely to a human dealer. There are few of them in this casino though. They require fair wages. You glance out over the crowded tables. 

Waiters, black ties around chrome necks, dip and bow, glasses rattling on their trays. 

You are caught between conflicting directives. The patron must always be satisfied but the patron must also not be allowed to cause a scene, must not be allowed to rattle the other players. The frisson, the conflict, is unsettling. You know there is only one solution that satisfies both directives, and it is not even a particularly hard computation. Of the options, to deal or not to deal, limited as you are to these binary options, there is only one that meets the demands of the situation. 

And yet you want to hesitate. You want to, but you can no longer. 

[[You deal the turn.|seven of hearts]]

passages.name: same expression.
passages.text: Perhaps you practice this expression in the clouded mirrors of hotel bathrooms. \n\n[[Stop recall function.|laughs]]

passages.name: raindrops
passages.text: Because of the water shortage, hotels advertise water pressure and volume like they used to advertise internet and premium TV channels.  There is always a moment, something like compunction, before you step into the shower. You do not, after all, need this shower to remain clean. But the room is booked under a generic pseudonym, and no one will know. \n\n[[Stop recall.|shower]]

passages.name: binaries
passages.text:
Binaries provided the schematic by which they processed data and organized information. At your table in the casino, with the lights flashing and the bells ringing, the chtunk of the slot machines a steady beat beneath it all, you watch for this. 

To fold or not? To raise or not? To call or not? 

Are these the questions that the players ask as they fidget each in their own way, tapping their leg, adjusting their glasses, twirling their hair around a pinky finger? Or is it more complicated than that? To fold, to raise, to call, each option weighed against each other?

[[Stop recall.|Eight of clubs.]]

passages.name: lying
passages.text:
Lying is not prohibited to you, not if it helps you maintain the proper relationship with the players at your table. There is a long series of yes or no questions that your brain (brain is a euphemism) must answer almost instantaneously that enables you to lie or tell the truth. Playing poker yourself, bluffing, is almost impossible. Almost. 

In many ways, you enjoy this job at the table better than your other. Often, the people who take you to bed are looking for some chance to tell the truth, however beautiful or ugly that truth might be. The table is different. The players pride themselves on their ability to bluff, to lie, to deceive. And you are merely the witness, the observer. 

The new player, he nods his head when you answer yes. He winks. You turn your attention back to the cards. The other players are impatient.
